<img loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-1343799 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_20210220_091154.jpg" alt="" width="1280" height="836" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_20210220_091154.jpg 720w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_20210220_091154-487x318.jpg 487w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_20210220_091154-320x209.jpg 320w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_20210220_091154-640x418.jpg 640w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_20210220_091154-600x392.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" />There seems to be no stopping the new Nigerian social impact movie, The New Patriots, as it has just been officially selected at both the Berlin Flash Film and Montreal Independent Film Festivals. It would be recalled that just recently, the movie was selected for the 2021 five continents International Film Festival in Venezuela in the Drama feature film category. The New Patriots is set in a fictional Republic of Aruguna and accentuates the disenchantment of the youth with the decadence in the society and their struggle to achieve sociopolitical transformation. The movie parades top grade actors like Akin Lewis, Lateef Adedimeji, Bimbo Oshin, Dele Odule, Taiwo Ibikunle and other talented thespians like Bimpe Oyebade, Damipe Adekoya, Bimbo Sunday among others. Set to hit the cinema soo, The New Patriots was directed by Adebayo Tijani and Terry Ayebo and produced by Dr. Rotimi Adelola of Number 9 Film Studio.